    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>http://ntmscope.org/authors/margo-diricks/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 09 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://ntmscope.org/authors/margo-diricks/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Margo Diricks is postdoctoral researcher and bioinformatics research scientist in the Molecular and Experimental Mycobacteriology group at the Research Center Borstel, Germany. She is interested in microbiology, antimicrobial resistance and molecular epidemiology of mycobacteria and other emerging lung pathogens. Currently, she is involved in different projects regarding molecular typing of bacteria, such as &lt;em&gt;Haemophilus influenzae&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;Mycobacterium abscessus&lt;/em&gt;. For the latter, she developed a cgMLST scheme to delineate global population structure and transmission and is curator of the publicly available M. abscessus 7-loci MLST scheme at pubmlst.org.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>http://ntmscope.org/authors/nils-wetzstein/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 09 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://ntmscope.org/authors/nils-wetzstein/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Nils Wetzstein is a consultant for infectious diseases at University Hospital Frankfurt (UHF). He has a keen interest in mycobacterial diseases and his research is primarily focussed on NTM infections. The working group of mycobacterial diseases at UHF uses a variety of bacteriological, epidemiological and bioinformatical methods to improve clinical management and patient care for MTB and NTM infected patients.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>http://ntmscope.org/authors/stefan-niemann/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 09 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://ntmscope.org/authors/stefan-niemann/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Stefan Niemann is Professor at the Research Center Borstel, Molecular and Experimental Mycobacteriology in Germany. He is molecular biologist with a large experience in molecular characterization of &lt;em&gt;M. tuberculosis&lt;/em&gt; complex isolates. His research interests are focused on the development of rapid diagnostics, the epidemiology of tuberculosis (TB), mechanisms of development and spread of resistance in clinical M. tuberculosis complex (MTBC) isolates, the microevolution in clinical MTBC isolates, the global population structure/evolution of the pathogen, and on the pathobiology and host-pathogen interaction. The following links provide more information on his research goals
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;a href=&#34;https://fz-borstel.de/index.php/en/sitemap/priority-research-area-infections-prof-dr-ulrich-schaible/molecular-and-experimental-mycobacteriology-prof-dr-stefan-niemann/mission#innercontent&#34;&gt;https://fz-borstel.de/index.php/en/sitemap/priority-research-area-infections-prof-dr-ulrich-schaible/molecular-and-experimental-mycobacteriology-prof-dr-stefan-niemann/mission#innercontent&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.tbsequel.org/personnel/stefan-niemann/&#34;&gt;https://www.tbsequel.org/personnel/stefan-niemann/&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Based on his achievements, he has been awarded the Eva and Klaus Grohe Prize of the Berlin-Brandenburg Academy of Sciences and Humanities in 2011, the Main Prize of the German Society for Hygiene and Microbiology in 2016, the DZIF Prize for Clinical Translational Infection Research in 2019, and the Gardner Middlebrook Award in 2021. He became W3 Professor for Molecular and Experimental Mycobacteriology at the University of Lübeck in 2014, one out of eight Schleswig-Holstein-Excellence-Chairs in 2016, and Visiting Professor of the University of Namibia in 2017.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>http://ntmscope.org/authors/thomas-a.-wichelhaus/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 09 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://ntmscope.org/authors/thomas-a.-wichelhaus/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Thomas A. Wichelhaus is Professor for Microbiology at the Institute for Medical Microbiology and Infection Control at University Hospital, Frankfurt. He is involved in different fields of clinical microbiology. As head of the diagnostic laboratory for Mycobacteria, he is highly interested in mycobacterial diseases such as NTM infections.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
